#: ./security-guide/section_tls-proxies-and-http-services.xml:35(para)
msgid "Before we delve into the configurations, we briefly discuss the ciphers' configuration element and its format. A more exhaustive treatment on available ciphers and the OpenSSL cipher list format can be found at: <link xlink:href=\"https://www.openssl.org/docs/apps/ciphers.html\">ciphers</link>."
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_tls-proxies-and-http-services.xml:43(para)
msgid "Cipher string options are separated by \":\", while \"!\" provides negation of the immediately following element. Element order indicates preference unless overridden by qualifiers such as HIGH. Let us take a closer look at the elements in the above sample strings."
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_tls-proxies-and-http-services.xml:46(code)
msgid "kEECDH:kEDH"
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_tls-proxies-and-http-services.xml:48(para)
msgid "Ephemeral Elliptic Curve Diffie-Hellman (abbreviated as EECDH and ECDHE)."
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_tls-proxies-and-http-services.xml:49(para)
msgid "Ephemeral Diffie-Hellman (abbreviated either as EDH or DHE) uses prime field groups."
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_tls-proxies-and-http-services.xml:50(para)
msgid "Both approaches provide <link xlink:href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forward_secrecy\"> Perfect Forward Secrecy (PFS)</link>. See <xref linkend=\"tls-proxies-and-http-services-perfect-forward-secrecy\"/> for additional discussion on properly configuring PFS."
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_tls-proxies-and-http-services.xml:56(para)
msgid "Ephemeral Elliptic Curves require the server to be configured with a named curve, and provide better security than prime field groups and at lower computational cost. However, prime field groups are more widely implemented, and thus typically both are included in list."
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_tls-proxies-and-http-services.xml:60(code)
msgid "kRSA"
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_tls-proxies-and-http-services.xml:62(para)
msgid "Cipher suites using the <link xlink:href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_%28cryptosystem%29\">RSA</link> exchange, authentication or either respectively."
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_tls-proxies-and-http-services.xml:66(code)
msgid "HIGH"
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_tls-proxies-and-http-services.xml:68(para)
msgid "Selects highest possible security cipher in the negotiation phase. These typically have keys of length 128 bits or longer."
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_tls-proxies-and-http-services.xml:72(code)
msgid "!RC4"
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_tls-proxies-and-http-services.xml:74(para)
msgid "No RC4. RC4 has flaws in the context of TLS V3. See <link xlink:href=\"http://cr.yp.to/streamciphers/rc4biases-20130708.pdf\"> On the Security of RC4 in TLS and WPA</link>."
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_tls-proxies-and-http-services.xml:78(code)
msgid "!MD5"
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_tls-proxies-and-http-services.xml:80(para)
msgid "No MD5. MD5 is not collision resistant, and thus not acceptable for Message Authentication Codes (MAC) or signatures."
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_tls-proxies-and-http-services.xml:84(code)
msgid "!aNULL:!eNULL"
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_tls-proxies-and-http-services.xml:86(para)
msgid "Disallows clear text."
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_tls-proxies-and-http-services.xml:90(code)
msgid "!EXP"
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_tls-proxies-and-http-services.xml:92(para)
msgid "Disallows export encryption algorithms, which by design tend to be weak, typically using 40 and 56 bit keys."
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_tls-proxies-and-http-services.xml:94(para)
msgid "US Export restrictions on cryptography systems have been lifted and no longer need to be supported."
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_tls-proxies-and-http-services.xml:98(code)
msgid "!LOW:!MEDIUM"
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_tls-proxies-and-http-services.xml:100(para)
msgid "Disallows low (56 or 64 bit long keys) and medium (128 bit long keys) ciphers because of their vulnerability to brute force attacks (example 2-DES). This rule still permits Triple Data Encryption Standard (Triple DES) also known as Triple Data Encryption Algorithm (TDEA) and the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES), each of which has keys greater than equal to 128 bits and thus more secure."
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_tls-proxies-and-http-services.xml:108(code)
msgid "Protocols"
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_tls-proxies-and-http-services.xml:110(para)
msgid "Protocols are enabled/disabled through SSL_CTX_set_options. We recommend disabling SSLv2/v3 and enabling TLS."
